Resale Flat Price

7 November 2019

Summary

  • Data sourced from: Resale Flat Price
  • Unsurpisingly, resale flats which fetch a higher price are ones that are bigger and higher.
  • Houses nearest to the MRT also fetch a higher price, but only within a distance of 1 km.

1. Set Up

library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(forcats)
library(geosphere)

RFP <- readr::read_csv("data/resale-flat-prices-based-on-registration-date-from-jan-2017-onwards.csv")
RFP = RFP %>%
  mutate(month = parse_date_time(month, "Ym"),
         town = as.factor(town),
         flat_type = as.factor(flat_type),
         address = paste("Block", block, street_name),
         storey_range = as.factor(storey_range),
         flat_model = as.factor(flat_model),
         months_left = year(period(remaining_lease)) * 12 + month(period(remaining_lease)),
         resale_price = resale_price / 1000
  )
options(scipen = 999)


2. Variable Relationship with Resale Prices

a. Towns

RFP %>%
  
  group_by(town) %>%
  summarise(mean.resale_price = mean(resale_price)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = mean.resale_price, x = fct_reorder(town, mean.resale_price))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#06d6a0") +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price between Towns",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()


b. Flat Type

RFP %>%
  
  group_by(flat_type) %>%
  summarise(mean.resale_price = mean(resale_price)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = mean.resale_price, x = fct_reorder(flat_type, mean.resale_price))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#ef476f") +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price between Flat Types",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

  • Unexpectedly, the bigger the house type, the higher the price


c. Storey Range

RFP %>%
  
  group_by(storey_range) %>%
  summarise(mean.resale_price = mean(resale_price)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = mean.resale_price, x = fct_reorder(storey_range, mean.resale_price))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#ffd166") +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price between Flat Types",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

  • Also unsurprisingly, the higher the flat, the higher the resale price.
  • Change in price appears to be lower at the lowest and highest storey ranges.


d. Floor Area

RFP %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = resale_price, x = floor_area_sqm)) +
  geom_point(col = "#06d6a0", alpha = 0.3) +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price against Floor Area",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "Floor Area (in square metres)") +
  theme_minimal()

  • The graph shows an interesting relationship between the two variables, where there appears to be a exponential relationship between the two variables; but at the same time a huge variance in the prices for each floor area.
RFP %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = resale_price, x = floor_area_sqm, col = storey_range)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3, size = 1.2) +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price against Floor Area",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "Floor Area (in square metres)",
       col = "") +
  theme_minimal()

  • Separating the colours by the storey range, the graph suggests that the difference in prices for each given floor area is likely due to the floor area.


e. Flat Model

RFP %>%
  
  group_by(flat_model) %>%
  summarise(mean.resale_price = mean(resale_price)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = mean.resale_price, x = fct_reorder(flat_model, mean.resale_price))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#26547c") +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price between Flat Models",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

  • As expected, flat models such as DBSS and Terraces fetch a higher resale price than normal HDBs.


f. Months Left

RFP %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = resale_price, x = months_left)) +
  geom_point(col = "#ef476f", alpha = 0.15) +
  geom_smooth() +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price over Time",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "Months Left") +
  theme_minimal()

  • Prices of HDB fluctuate over time, but the trend is that prices decrease over time.
  • Variace for each given month left is likely due other variables such as floor area, town and flat type.


3. Location to MRT

Geocoding each address

unique_addr <- unique(RFP$address)
register_google(key = api)
addr_geocode <- geocode(unique_addr)

addr_df = cbind(unique_addr, addr_geocode)
addr_df_complete = addr_df[ , c(2, 4, 5)]
colnames(addr_df_complete) = c("address", "long", "lat")
  • Addresses were geocoded using the google maps api, and the mrt locations were geocoded and saved.
  • Unique addresses were geocoded as it reduced the number of geocodes from 56 to 8 thousand.
  • Also, geocoding uses credits.
addr_df_complete = read.csv("data/addr_df_complete.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
mrt_locations = read.csv("data/MRT_locations.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  
for (i in 1:NROW(addr_df_complete)) {
  
  addr_df_complete$nearestMRTdist[i] = 
    distHaversine(p1 = addr_df_complete[i, c("long", "lat")],
                  p2 = mrt_locations[ , c("long", "lat")]) %>% 
    min()
}
  • distHaversine function was used to calculate the distance between each address to all mrt locations, based on their long and lat values.
RFP = left_join(RFP, addr_df_complete, by = "address")


b. Relationship between Distance to Nearest MRT and Resale Price

RFP %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = resale_price, x = nearestMRTdist)) +
  geom_point(col = "#06d6a0", alpha = 0.15) +
  geom_smooth() +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price against Distance to Nearest MRT",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)",
       x = "Distance (m)") +
  theme_minimal()

  • Graph is a little confusing
RFP %>%
  mutate(group = cut(nearestMRTdist, 
                     breaks = seq(0, 4000, by = 200), 
                     labels = seq(200, 4000, by = 200))) %>%
  group_by(group) %>%
  summarise(mean.resale_price = mean(resale_price)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(y = mean.resale_price, x = group)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#26547c") +
  
  labs(title = "Graph of Mean Resale Price against Distance to Nearest MRT",
       x = "Distance (m)",
       y = "Mean Resale Price (in thousands)") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 500, 100)) +
  theme_minimal()

  • Flats nearer to the MRT fetch a higher price, but the effect tapers out at about 1 km away from the MRT. Following which there is a slight incline.
